segments.text: Well they had movies in Guyon Hall that were pretty inexpensive.
I can remember going to them on Saturday evening and the campus theater was there.
There were two theaters in downtown Bryan or three.
One of them is the one that burned, you know, that has, I don't remember going to a lot of movies, but I remember going to a few.
And you never were a smoker?
No.
I didn't uh, I didn't ever really get started.
I smoked a few cigarettes my freshman year, decided that it was done, and just never did go any further.
Uh, uh, did you and your buddies go to the MSC much?
Snack bar?
Cokes, coffee?
Yeah, I remember uh, uh,

going for uh some kind you know a coke or a coffee or something in the MSC and I was just talking to someone the other day uh there was a friend of mine Doug With that I have you know knew all of his life after that point in history but I remember the first time I met him was in the MSC in that coffee shop he was a senior the year I was a freshman so

those things living in the core with this responsibility to meet everybody to remember where they're from to remember where they're what they're majoring in and everything it just made you it made individuals made impressions on you that you know stayed with you for years and years was it in the long run was that a good a good practice
Was it worth the effort?
Yes.
I think that there were some really positive things about the Corps.
There were some negatives, too, but the... What were the positives?
Well, being personally responsible for meeting people and being able to, you know,

have a conversation with anybody in the world and to you know remember who they were when you saw them again and after a while we got very good at remembering names and you know we had a unit of a hundred people we knew everybody's name where they were all from what their majors were
In a lot of cases, if they had a brother that had come to A&M, we knew that.
So any A&M connection in these families, we would more than likely know something about that.
Most of the people I knew were the first, we were the first person in the family that had ever gone to A&M.
So it was more unusual in those days to have your father to have been an A&M graduate.
Did you get involved in any MSC activities or were they not yet well organized?
The MSC was not too far along at that time as far as a campus organization.
I know just a year or two after me, one of my 4-H friends, his name was Don McGinty and he
he became very active and eventually became a MSC council president, one of the first ones, I guess.
So I was in the club for range and forestry students and I was in the Alpha Zeta agricultural fraternity.
I was on the Ag Council.
I, of course, I was in the Ross Volunteers.
I was in the debate, on the debate team.
Those are the, the main things I remember.
There was Phi Kappa Phi my senior year.
So, so there were a lot of evening activities after my,
freshman year.
I don't remember doing any of that my freshman year.
Alright, you came back that fall of your sophomore year with a car?
Yes, some, right, I think actually sometime during my sophomore year I got that car.
What kind of car was it?
It was a 1941 Chevrolet Coupe.
So this is.
I had one of those.
I wish I had that.
Mine was a business coupe.

Yeah this was uh it was a coupe it had a sun visor on it it had fender skirts on it it had it had a metallic green paint job that you could see from them two miles away you know it was a beautiful thing.
A vehicle that was 10-11 years old did you think of that as an old car or kind of a?
Well it was kind of an old car but
I didn't really think of it as being a negative, you know.
There were, it was, you, if you had a car you were still above average at that point.
Where did you park it?
Well there were, there were parking lots near the dorms.
I was in dorm 12 that year.
Because you didn't have to have a sticker.
I guess so.
And you never did have any, didn't have any breaking or?
No.
I don't remember ever having anybody ever talking about a car being stolen or a car being broken into.
Did you become a more popular guy with your associates once you got a car that they would want to ride with you or borrow it?
I don't remember that I don't remember that I don't remember loaning it out a lot and I guess if I'd been you know if I'd been going out at night well that but even as even as sophomores we still
had a lot of restrictions on where we could go and whether we could leave the campus or not.
How was being a sophomore different from being a freshman?
Well, I decided that as a sophomore I wanted to do the academics, do the leadership things, and I was not particularly interested in harassing freshmen.
I didn't.
So the main thing that I remember about being a sophomore was the pressure of being in the Corps was less.
And where was your outfit then, physically?
Physically, that year it seems like we were in Dormitory 12 next door to Sabisa.
Excuse me, Duncan.
To Duncan.
Yeah, right.
And so you didn't harass the, you didn't?
Oh, not a lot.
Did somebody come and take care of your room or do any cleaning up for you?
No.
No.
There was not much personal service.
That was an ongoing problem, but I, you know, rarely ever saw that.
Rarely was, I was, as a freshman, I was never asked to give personal service.
As a sophomore,

because we were the low-ranking people in the unit, occasionally somebody would want their boots polished, and then it was a real judgment call as to whether you said no or whether you did it, you know, and some people would say no and other people would be afraid to say no, and they would do the boot polishing, but that was about the extent of the personal service.
And you're digging in on your grades.
Have you, by that point, changed your mind as to what you hoped your future goal was going to be professionally?
I think by that time I was beginning to realize that I was going to need to find a job and make a living not as a rancher, but as somebody developing a profession.
But my vision was not beyond the BS at that time.
And I, for reasons that I don't understand now, became, you know, convinced that I was not going to go to graduate school.
I was just going to be a regular fellow, you know.
I'm going to get a BS and go out and make a living and that was going to be it.
And I persisted in that until I graduated
and worked for a while and was so discouraged by the apparent lack of opportunities in the area that I was working in.
Now there weren't many graduate students on this campus then, were there?
That's right.
They weren't very visible and very unlikely you could talk to them.
about what it was like and what they were doing.
Did that sophomore year, were there, there weren't any particular changes on the campus, nothing, nothing unusual or anything?
Not that I remember.

that was the era that David Morgan came as president and I guess that we I thought that was a very positive thing and I heard him speak to the range and forestry club and I thought he was a very sensible man and he had a lot of good advice for us and he gave us a talk about
how to get started in your career.

And I remember he told us that the most likely thing that a graduate would do with his first job was quit in less than a year out of discouragement, you know, and thinking that he never could get anywhere and that sort of thing.
And he said, if you do that, you make a mistake.
And I remember that.
But for some reason, he didn't last very long.

That may have been my first exposure to, you know, sort of an ongoing problem at A&M of palace intrigues or turnover in the administration or personal conflicts between various people in the administration.
Now, did you get, by this time, were you involved with the local congregation?
No, I wasn't.
I was my wife-to-be, and I were from different churches.
And so during that time in my life, I was trying to decide what I was going to do about that as a possible problem for a marriage.
And eventually, that was resolved.
I became a member of the Church of Christ after we were married.
Did you, while you were a student here, did you go to any religious services?
I went to the Baptist Church at Northgate a little bit.
Some of my acquaintances who were members of Churches of Christ took me to Bryan.
I don't remember
ever attending the Church of Christ in College Station while I was an undergraduate.
Uh, and were there some Sunday night foods, foods available at some of those, uh, uh, events?
I never got involved in any of that for some reason.
I, I know that since then, you know, the church that I'm involved in now does a lot of that, you know, but I, I don't remember ever experiencing that.
So for me, at Austin College, that was one of the big things.
Because we didn't have Sunday night supper.
They gave us a brown bag.
But the Westminster Fellowship ladies cooked a meal, so we all.
And we snickered that we were rice Christians, that we went only to get the list for the food.
Do you remember Religious Emphasis Week during your undergraduate days?
Yes.
Describe it.
What was it like?
Well, it was a pretty big thing.
in those days and I remember they had they had one session a day in Gine Hall everybody would go and listen and then there would be somebody either not not every dorm had a lounge in it

but the dorms that had lounges would have discussion groups and these would be led by out of town ministers too and so it just would sort of depend on who you know I guess you didn't really have any control over
who was assigned to the dorm where you were to go.
But I remember going to all of those and thinking they were useful and productive and that the people had good ideas.
And I would always come out feeling very optimistic and thinking, well, I'm going to be a better person and everything.
And classes were dismissed mid-morning, weren't they?
And wasn't there a sermon in or presentation in Guyon?
Yes.
Did I say rudder?
Maybe I did.
No, no, I don't know.
So that was right.
You had like 10 o'clock to 11 or 10 o'clock to 11 30 or something.
There was an hour off each day during that week.
And I remember the attendance was pretty good.
During the
the Korean War is still going on during this time.
Did you and your buddies talk about that much and chow and dining and dormitory and so forth?
I don't remember talking about it much.
There were people that were that were people that left school or people that flunked out were going immediately into the military.

we had people that were graduating that were being killed before you know within a year of when they graduated I remember the guy that was the head jail leader my freshman year was dead before football season was over the next year or something like that so it was a ominous presence especially I remember feeling sort of really uh

discouraged about the war during the time when the Chinese first entered the war and they were just sweeping down over overrunning units and everything and and we knew enough about that to know you know what what was happening there or sort of in in general what was happening but I never did
I never did feel like that it was something that I needed to worry about personally.
I really expected that when my four years was up that I would, you know, get ready and go and do my tour.
And it was a bit of a surprise that it was actually settled before I graduated or shortly after I graduated.
When I graduated, well, I had orders for, I think, December of the following, well, of that year, and those orders were changed then, and they were changed from two years active duty to
to six months active duty for training.
So that was sort of the, that was one of the events that probably pushed me in the direction of an academic career because it put... Did you go to summer camp after your sophomore year?
After my junior year.
Junior year.
Yes.
What was that like?
Where was it and so forth?
Summer camp for the Transportation Corps was at Fort Eustis, Virginia.
Tidewater area, hot summers, humid, just like College Station.
We were there with people from all over the United States, but I remember we had a big competition with the unit that had all of the Texas, University of Texas guys in it, and
We were determined to have the best unit at summer camp, you know.
So, and I think we ended up sort of in a dead heat with them.
They didn't want us to show them up and so they did their best to compete with us on everything.
Could you tell at summer camp that the Corps had given you and your buddies a good preparation?
for active duty possibilities?
Yes.
And we were amazed at how little some of the guys were prepared for anything military.
And we felt good about our preparation.

Now there weren't any sudden events were there during your undergraduate days that you remember where you were when you heard the news that like Pearl Harbor for the earlier group and Kennedy assassination later there was nothing like that was there?
No.
A startling event that stopped everything?
I don't remember anything like that while I was in school.
Not at all.
Were there any celebrity students?
Who were the most visible students on the campus when you were here, then or now?
Well then the celebrity students would have been either athletes or.
Such as?
There was a, there was a, I think it was during my undergraduate time there was a guy that was a football player and a shot putter named Darryl Hooper who competed in the Olympics.
There was a guy named Davis who played basketball and was a high jumper and competed in the Olympics.
Did guys like that go to class regularly, as far as you knew?
As far as I knew, they did.
Did you and your buddies know about any kind of crip courses or special giveaway grade points for anybody?
No.
There was the campus rumors were that if you wanted the best old quiz files to study for anything that the athletes had them.
But there was in those days there was no indication that they had the quizzes before they were given or anything like that.
And as far as you knew athletes went to class?
Yes, and a lot of those, you know, I remember one of the football players was Larry Winkler from Temple area.
He was in a lot of my classes, was just an ordinary person.
In fact, he said that, you know, until

he was small as a high schooler and gruesome after his senior year and I don't think he even had a scholarship when he came to A&M but he played his way onto the team and ended up with the scholarship and there were a lot of people like that there were uh I guess there were some

some elitist type athletes that were just athletes, you know, especially, uh, when I was a freshman, uh, uh, there were two or three quite well-known running backs, uh, Smith, Robert Smith, and a few other people.
But, but people like Yale Larry, you know,

played his senior year played fullback some when Smith got hurt and you know weighed 150 pounds or something you know and you just think he couldn't do it and and that just you know gave everybody the impression that they were just uh just like everybody else were there any contemporaries of yours that have now gone on to world fame national fame
Gotten rich, served in a certain office, been president of.
I can't think of any of those people in my class that have exceeded, you know, in those kinds of, at those levels.
Describe the A&M student body in general.
Where were they from?
What kinds of backgrounds?
What kinds of attitudes?
What kind of economic groups and so forth?
Well, in those days there were, as I recall, there were almost 2,000 freshmen in 1951.
There were quite a few from Houston and San Antonio and Dallas-Fort Worth, but
Once you got past that point, most of them were from small towns.
Most of them were from Texas.
If they weren't from Texas, more than likely there was some family connection to A&M.
And they were not so many that were from well-to-do families.
So that was part of the explanation for there not being a,
a large number of cars and they weren't all new cars by any stretch of the imagination.
And I remember having a friend whose father owned an automobile agency, you know, and we all thought of him as being upper, you know, upper economic class.
So that sort of, you know, illustrated that we were all from
pretty far down the economic ladder.
Did your family background really matter here among the student body?

No, not, you know, that's one thing that they told us when we came was that you're going to be in a big fraternity and all you've got to, it doesn't matter what your family background is or how much money you have or you don't have,
you're going to be judged on your performance.
And we saw that with the Hispanic students.
And there were quite a few in those days.
And of all my regrets about the A&M traditions, one of them is that there weren't as many black students in those days.
In other words, if A&M at that stage in the history of Texas and the South had

had voluntarily admitted blacks at that time I think we'd have another thing to be proud of in our heritage but but our but the Hispanic students were accepted based on just the judgment that was passed on everybody else did they
pull their share of the load, did they follow the rules, you know, all of those sorts of things.
And true also for Jewish kids, was it?
Yes.
Jewish kids, I knew a few, and I remember one of my professors I learned was Jewish, and he was the first adult, you know, Jew, I suppose, that I'd ever known.
And I remember that he was in the chemistry department, was an excellent teacher, and everybody had a good, you know, I never heard anyone say anything negative about him.
And it didn't matter how much your family made or didn't make, it was how you were a part of the group, is that right?
Yes.
Did lots of students have nicknames then?
Quite a few.
Did you?
No, I don't.
I'm trying to remember about that.
I did not have a nickname, but especially the students that

that got into trouble quote unquote you know the ones that were always saying the wrong thing at the wrong time or something like that they would get a what they would call a handle and they they would have to introduce themselves as
Fish I always mess up whenever I get excited, Jones is my name or something like that, you know.
So, and sometimes those would be temporary and sometimes they'd be sort of permanent.
Fortunately, I didn't get hung with one of those.
Part of my strategy was to kind of keep a low profile and not get into all kinds of trouble.
Among the student body, what were the most prestigious leadership positions on the entire campus?
Well, we saw the core staff.
as more visible and more important to the day-to-day student life than the student body president or who was not so important.
I guess the non, the students that weren't in the core were mostly veterans, mostly totally here for academics, trying to graduate as quickly as possible.
And so,

And the core generated enough work for, you know, most everybody to have plenty to do and it wasn't until there was a significant part of the student body that wasn't in the core that there was a surplus of leadership to do the big MSC development and other things like that.
So that was before the time of the student
National Affairs, SCONA things, you know, all of that.
What about the Yale leaders?
Yale leaders were very visible.
What did you all think of the band?
Well, I can't remember ever having any
anything but admiration for the band as a whole and some of people that were in transportation corps in our classes ROTC classes could be in the band and so they were all good friends
I don't remember much else about it.
The Corps always had these fierce competitions for marching and marching and who would win this and that.
